      %h3 How to pick the right boots – where to start 

      .article-image.aspect-3-4
        -second_url = image_path("blog/big-boots/big-boots-long-coat.jpg")
        =image_tag(second_url, alt: "Standing confidently on stone steps, wearing black knee-high boots, a black fedora, black and white thigh-length dress and a long black and white coat.")
        %figcaption
          Photo by
          =link_to('marymarkevich', 'https://www.freepik.com/free-photo/attractive-young-woman-walking-autumn-wearing-coat_27290198.htm')
          on Freepik

      %p
        The next step is knowing your autumn/winter needs.
        This will go a long way to helping you make the right choice.
        If you get it right now, your boots will be a perfect match for both your autumn wardrobe as well as the harsher weather to come for winter.
        Trust me your feet and your wallet will thank you for it by the end of December.
        My first perfect boots lasted me right up until spring the following year and they still look amazing.

      %p
        So, before you choose your big boots, it’s important to know what type and style you want and will suit you the best,
        and more importantly, which style will last you the full season.
        If you build on what you already have and what style you wear most often, you can’t go wrong and your boots and your wardrobe will always match.
        This will ultimately give you less stress when getting ready and save you so much time.

      %h3
        Key things to remember

      %p
        Here are a few things that you should think about before you make your big boots choice:

      %ul
        %li
          Think about your height and frame and consider what style of garments you are most likely to wear on your lower half.
        %li
          If you like the bottom of your trousers to sit inside your boots then think about leggings or fitted jeans, which are often the best option with big boots,
          but if you like the bottom of your trousers to hang outside of your boots, then bootcut or straight-leg jeans or regular trousers might be a better fit.
          Your garment should always meet your boots nicely and be comfortable too.
        %li
          Some mid-calf boots can be quite long and sometimes reduce the appearance of length on a shorter leg.
          You might prefer an ankle or Chelsea boot to avoid this.
        %li
          Another thing to think about is the sole. If you are happy with a few extra inches, then oversized or bigger soles are just the thing for you.
          These also tend to last longer.
        %li
          If you are happy with your current height or are already on the tall side then a thinner sole might be much better.
          It is definitely something to think about.

